<paragraph blockId="20.[806,1422,763,1245]" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis box="[806,925,764,785]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
This subgenus is distinguishable from the other subgenera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kraatz" authorityYear="1857" box="[1032,1165,794,815]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hoplandria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1032,1165,794,815]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Hoplandria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: body large to very large (
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="13.5" metricValueMin="4.5" pageId="20" pageNumber="103" unit="mm" value="9.0" valueMax="13.5" valueMin="4.5">4.5– 13.5 mm</quantity>
); body colouration pale throughout or more or less bicoloured; pronotum unevenly and generally weakly pubescent, with six large setiferous pores; males with each elytron with distinct humeral carina or bump, distinct denticle, carina or conical process on the medioapical region, a well-developed denticle, carina or bump on the outer apical third, and a distinct carina on lateral margins; posterior corner of abdominal sternum 
<collectionCode box="[963,993,1101,1122]" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">III</collectionCode>
slightly modified or extended, generally not as a long spine, abdominal tergum 
<collectionCode box="[1331,1359,1132,1153]" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">IV</collectionCode>
with highly variable, raised flat area on tergum 
<collectionCode box="[1325,1353,1162,1183]" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">IV</collectionCode>
often appearing irridescent; and abdominal tergum VII with generally narrow posteromedian longtitudinal carina.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[806,1422,1269,1445]" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis box="[806,942,1270,1291]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Description:</emphasis>
In agreement with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kraatz" authorityYear="1857" box="[1187,1320,1269,1290]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hoplandria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1187,1320,1269,1290]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Hoplandria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
description, except for the following characters. [1] Lengths of adults 
<quantity box="[896,1047,1331,1353]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="13.5" metricValueMin="4.5" pageId="20" pageNumber="103" unit="mm" value="9.0" valueMax="13.5" valueMin="4.5">4.5–13.5 mm</quantity>
. [2] Body (
<figureCitation box="[1201,1297,1331,1353]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="21.[155,233,1778,1797]" captionTargetBox="[158,1443,205,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-60@21.[154,1446,193,1750]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 10. Hoplandria (Platonica) major (Sharp). (A) Habitus, dorsal view. (B) Labrum. (C) Epipharynx. (D) Mandible, dorsal view. (E) Mandible, ventral view. (F) Maxilla. (G) Labium. (H) Hypopharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437814/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
) typically highly fusiform; with [4] large, distinctive punctation and microsculpturing; [5,6,7,8,9] pubescence generally sparse throughout.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[806,1422,1468,1675]" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis box="[806,874,1469,1490]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Head:</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[894,989,1469,1491]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="21.[155,233,1778,1797]" captionTargetBox="[158,1443,205,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-60@21.[154,1446,193,1750]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 10. Hoplandria (Platonica) major (Sharp). (A) Habitus, dorsal view. (B) Labrum. (C) Epipharynx. (D) Mandible, dorsal view. (E) Mandible, ventral view. (F) Maxilla. (G) Labium. (H) Hypopharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437814/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
) [10] Typically as wide as long. [11] Eyes generally large, 0.4–0.7 times length of head. [13] Infraorbital carina more or less strongly developed and complete. Antenna with [15] articles 1–3 elongate, 2.5–3.5 times longer than wide; [16] article 4 slightly elongate; [17] articles 5–10 short, 1.0–2.0 times wider than long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[806,1422,1699,1905]" lastBlockId="22.[806,1422,1392,1782]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="105" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis box="[806,946,1699,1720]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Mouthparts:</emphasis>
Labrum (
<figureCitation box="[1073,1169,1699,1721]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="21.[155,233,1778,1797]" captionTargetBox="[158,1443,205,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-60@21.[154,1446,193,1750]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 10. Hoplandria (Platonica) major (Sharp). (A) Habitus, dorsal view. (B) Labrum. (C) Epipharynx. (D) Mandible, dorsal view. (E) Mandible, ventral view. (F) Maxilla. (G) Labium. (H) Hypopharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437814/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
) with epipharyngeal area with [19] medial pores small, numerous, more or less uniformly distributed in [20] very poorly delimited, longitudinal sensory field; [21] pores between longitudinal sensory field and lateral sclerotized areas few, primarly distributed apical and basal groups (
<figureCitation box="[814,912,1883,1905]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="21.[155,233,1778,1797]" captionTargetBox="[158,1443,205,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-60@21.[154,1446,193,1750]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 10. Hoplandria (Platonica) major (Sharp). (A) Habitus, dorsal view. (B) Labrum. (C) Epipharynx. (D) Mandible, dorsal view. (E) Mandible, ventral view. (F) Maxilla. (G) Labium. (H) Hypopharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437814/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
). Mandible (
<figureCitation box="[1063,1183,1883,1905]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="21.[155,233,1778,1797]" captionTargetBox="[158,1443,205,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-60@21.[154,1446,193,1750]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 10. Hoplandria (Platonica) major (Sharp). (A) Habitus, dorsal view. (B) Labrum. (C) Epipharynx. (D) Mandible, dorsal view. (E) Mandible, ventral view. (F) Maxilla. (G) Labium. (H) Hypopharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437814/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="103">Fig. 10D,E</figureCitation>
) with [24] condylar molar patch very small, width less than 1/8 of basal mandibular width, [25] composed of very small denticles or spinules, [26] densely arranged in more or less irregular transverse rows; dorsobasal ‘velvety patch’ [28] moderate in size, as wide as half of mandibular base, composed of [29] numerous, very fine hairs or spinules; [30] ventral aspect with outer basal angle with no setae. Maxilla (
<figureCitation box="[439,534,1606,1629]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="21.[155,233,1778,1797]" captionTargetBox="[158,1443,205,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-60@21.[154,1446,193,1750]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 10. Hoplandria (Platonica) major (Sharp). (A) Habitus, dorsal view. (B) Labrum. (C) Epipharynx. (D) Mandible, dorsal view. (E) Mandible, ventral view. (F) Maxilla. (G) Labium. (H) Hypopharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437814/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="105">Fig. 10F</figureCitation>
) with [32] lacinia more or less acute apically, [33] teeth of adoral margin short, about 3 times longer than wide, placed into [35] two distinct regions; [37] galea moderately narrow, narrower than lacinia at widest area, [38] membranous in apical 1/3–1/4. Labium (
<figureCitation box="[517,615,1760,1782]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="21.[155,233,1778,1797]" captionTargetBox="[158,1443,205,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-60@21.[154,1446,193,1750]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 10. Hoplandria (Platonica) major (Sharp). (A) Habitus, dorsal view. (B) Labrum. (C) Epipharynx. (D) Mandible, dorsal view. (E) Mandible, ventral view. (F) Maxilla. (G) Labium. (H) Hypopharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437814/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="105">Fig. 10G</figureCitation>
) with ligula [45] elongate, as long as labial palpus 1, with [47] forked apex; [49] two relatively long medial setae of prementum present, typically longer than ligula, [50] insertion of setae distinctly separated; [53] median pseudopore field wide and more or less rectangular; hypoglossal lobes (
<figureCitation box="[1039,1137,1422,1445]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="21.[155,233,1778,1797]" captionTargetBox="[158,1443,205,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-60@21.[154,1446,193,1750]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 10. Hoplandria (Platonica) major (Sharp). (A) Habitus, dorsal view. (B) Labrum. (C) Epipharynx. (D) Mandible, dorsal view. (E) Mandible, ventral view. (F) Maxilla. (G) Labium. (H) Hypopharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437814/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="105">Fig. 10H</figureCitation>
) [56] with moderately long, about 4 times longer than width of lobe, comblike internally curved setae; [57a] adoral setal patch typically expanded around lobe diameter. Labial palpi (
<figureCitation box="[814,911,1545,1567]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="21.[155,233,1778,1797]" captionTargetBox="[158,1443,205,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-60@21.[154,1446,193,1750]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 10. Hoplandria (Platonica) major (Sharp). (A) Habitus, dorsal view. (B) Labrum. (C) Epipharynx. (D) Mandible, dorsal view. (E) Mandible, ventral view. (F) Maxilla. (G) Labium. (H) Hypopharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437814" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437814/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="105">Fig. 10G</figureCitation>
) [58] very long and narrow, overall length 10–15 times longer than greatest width, [60] with distal pore field composed of two small spines; [61] article 1 about 3.5–4.0 times longer than article 2, [62] article 3 about 2.5 times longer than article 2. 
<collectingRegion box="[1264,1361,1668,1689]" country="Myanmar" name="Chin" pageId="22" pageNumber="105">Mentum</collectingRegion>
with [65] apical margin slightly to significantly concave with [67] many sensory pores typically distributed throughout.
</paragraph>
